{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532580"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:28:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:28:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14694"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14694"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.01,0.09,0.67,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88412"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7387"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72611"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"99"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1693"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6519"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45751"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88412"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset severe shortness of breath and chest pain for the past two hours. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed and diaphoretic. Her pulse rate is 120/min and irregular, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are widespread coarse crackles throughout both lung fields. Cardiovascular examination reveals a grade 6/6 pan-systolic murmur best heard at the apex and radiating to the axilla. The jugular venous pressure is elevated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHigh-sensitivity troponin I is 2500 ng/L (0-16). The electrocardiogram shows ST-segment elevation in leads II, III, and aVF with ST depression in leads I and aVL.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following coronary arteries is most likely to be occluded?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left anterior descending artery","First diagonal branch","Left circumflex artery","Right coronary artery","First obtuse marginal branch"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of acute severe mitral regurgitation complicating an acute inferior myocardial infarction. The combination of acute pulmonary oedema, new loud systolic murmur, and hypotension suggests papillary muscle rupture, a mechanical complication of myocardial infarction. The ECG findings of ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF with reciprocal ST depression in leads I and aVL are classic for inferior wall myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight coronary artery\u003C/strong\u003E occlusion is the most likely culprit as it typically supplies the posteromedial papillary muscle and the inferior wall of the left ventricle. This muscle is more susceptible to rupture because it has a single blood supply (either from the right coronary artery or circumflex artery), whereas the anterolateral papillary muscle has dual blood supply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft anterior descending artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the anterolateral papillary muscle and anterior wall. Occlusion typically causes anterior ST elevation (in leads V1-V4) and would be less likely to cause papillary muscle rupture due to dual blood supply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft circumflex artery\u003C/strong\u003E can sometimes supply the posteromedial papillary muscle, but right coronary artery dominance is more common (around 80% of people). The ECG changes in this case are more consistent with right coronary artery occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst diagonal branch\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the anterolateral wall and would not typically cause inferior ST changes or papillary muscle dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst obtuse marginal branch\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the lateral wall and would be unlikely to cause inferior ST changes or isolated papillary muscle dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe development of acute severe mitral regurgitation in this setting is most likely due to posteromedial papillary muscle rupture, which is a surgical emergency requiring urgent mechanical support and definitive repair.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute mitral regurgitation following myocardial infarction is most commonly due to papillary muscle rupture, particularly the posteromedial papillary muscle.","The posteromedial papillary muscle is supplied by a single coronary artery (right coronary or circumflex) making it more susceptible to infarction.","Acute severe mitral regurgitation presents with sudden onset pulmonary oedema and a new loud systolic murmur."],"references":["Uptodate: Papillary muscle rupture post infarction.","Papillary Muscle Rupture Complicating Acute Myocardial Infarction: A Tale of Teamwork.Lyana Labrada, Aadhar Patil, Jeevan Kumar, Samuel Kolman, Omer Iftikhar, Martin Keane, Kenji Minakata, William Van Decker, Vladimir Lakhter, and Isaac Whitman.J Am Coll Cardiol Case Rep. 2020 Dec, 2 (15) 2283\u20132288"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72611"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14694"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72611"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-03T22:24:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-03T22:24:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7387"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88412"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degre